#: src\architecture.md:65
msgid "Building OpenBabel from source"
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:67
msgid ""
"`openbabel-sys/build.rs` compiles OpenBabel as part of the crate build, so "
"there is no runtime dependency on a system OpenBabel install. Its pipeline:"
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:70
msgid ""
"**Build + install OpenBabel** from the `vendor/openbabel-src` submodule into "
"`OUT_DIR` using the [`cmake`](https://docs.rs/cmake) crate. Eigen (from "
"`vendor/eigen`) is pointed at OpenBabel's `find_package(Eigen3)`, which "
"enables `HAVE_EIGEN3` — this compiles `OBAlign` (structure superposition) "
"and unlocks distance-geometry 3D generation."
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:75
msgid ""
"**Compile the cxx bridge + shim**, pointing the C++ compiler at the freshly "
"installed OpenBabel headers."
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:77
msgid "**Link** against the OpenBabel import library."
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:78
msgid ""
"**Make the runtime discoverable**: bake the plugin/data directory paths into "
"a generated `paths.rs`, and (on Windows, which has no rpath) copy "
"`openbabel-3.dll` and its plugins next to the test/exe binaries."
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:82
msgid ""
"The first build compiles all of OpenBabel and is slow (~10–20 minutes); "
"subsequent builds are incremental unless the shim or bridge changes. See "
"[Building & Platform Notes](./building.md) for the MSVC-specific fixes this "
"script applies."
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:87
msgid "Thread safety: one global lock"
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:89
msgid ""
"**OpenBabel is not thread-safe.** It keeps global mutable state — shared "
"plugin singletons, aromaticity/ring-perception caches, and so on — so "
"concurrent calls from multiple threads can corrupt memory."
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:93
msgid ""
"Because `openbabel` exposes a _safe_ API, it must make that corruption "
"impossible. It does so by serializing **every** entry into OpenBabel behind "
"a single global lock. The mechanism is a small helper in "
"`openbabel/src/lib.rs`:"
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:107
msgid ""
"Every FFI call goes through `with_ob`. Two consequences worth internalizing:"
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:109
msgid ""
"**Calls from multiple threads are correct but do not run concurrently.** For "
"throughput, use multiple _processes_ rather than threads."
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:111
msgid ""
"**The lock is not reentrant.** Inside a `with_ob` closure, keep the raw "
"`ffi::…` calls only — never call back into a public method that would itself "
"take the lock, or you will deadlock. This is why the internal code passes "
"around `as_inner()` / `as_inner_pin_mut()` handles inside the closure."
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:116
msgid "Runtime initialization: finding plugins and data"
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:118
msgid ""
"OpenBabel loads its format plugins (`.obf`) from `BABEL_LIBDIR` and reads "
"element/forcefield data from `BABEL_DATADIR`, both lazily on first use. The "
"safe API sets these for you, exactly once, via `init()` (called from "
"`with_ob`):"
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:122
msgid ""
"The paths point at the plugin/data directories **bundled with the linked "
"library** (baked in by `build.rs`), so they always match the OpenBabel "
"version you built."
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:125
msgid ""
"They are set through the **C runtime** (`ffi::set_env`), not "
"`std::env::set_var`. On Windows, OpenBabel reads them with `getenv()`, which "
"does not observe variables set through the Win32 environment block that "
"`std::env` uses."
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:128
msgid ""
"`init()` **overrides** any pre-existing values. A stale system OpenBabel "
"install often leaves `BABEL_DATADIR` pointing at its own, version-mismatched "
"data directory, which silently breaks data-driven plugins (descriptors, some "
"fingerprints). The bundled data must match the bundled library."
msgstr ""

#: src\architecture.md:133
msgid ""
"You rarely call `init()` yourself — the public API does it — but it is `pub` "
"and idempotent if you want to force it early."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:3
msgid ""
"A category-by-category map of what the `openbabel` crate can do. For the "
"exact signatures of every method mentioned here, see the [API "
"Reference](./api-reference.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:7
msgid "Core: molecules, atoms, bonds"
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:9
msgid ""
"**I/O** — `Molecule::parse(data, format)` and `Molecule::write(format)` read "
"and write any OpenBabel format (`smi`, `mol`, `sdf`, `pdb`, `inchi`, "
"canonical SMILES `can`, …)."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:12
msgid ""
"**Properties** — `formula`, `molar_mass`, `exact_mass`, `total_charge`, "
"`num_atoms`, `num_bonds`, `title`."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:14
msgid ""
"**Atoms** (`Molecule::atoms` / `atom`) — element, coordinates, formal "
"charge, aromaticity, ring membership, and much more (see _Extended queries_ "
"below)."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:16
msgid ""
"**Bonds** (`Molecule::bonds` / `bond`) — begin/end atoms, order, "
"aromaticity, ring membership."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:18
msgid "**Hydrogens** — `add_hydrogens` / `remove_hydrogens`."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:20
msgid "Analysis"
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:22
msgid ""
"**SMARTS substructure matching** — `SmartsPattern::new(pattern)`, then "
"`matches`, `num_matches`, `match_indices`."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:24
msgid ""
"**Fingerprints & similarity** — `Fingerprint::compute(&mol, id)` for `FP2`, "
"`FP3`, `FP4`, `MACCS`, …, and `Fingerprint::tanimoto` for similarity."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:26
msgid ""
"**Numeric descriptors** — `Molecule::descriptor(id)`, plus the convenience "
"methods `logp`, `tpsa`, `molar_refractivity`."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:29
msgid "3D structures & force fields"
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:31
msgid ""
"**3D generation** — `generate_3d` / `generate_3d_with`; query with "
"`dimension` and `has_3d`."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:33
msgid ""
"**Force fields** — single-point `energy(forcefield)` and geometry "
"optimization `optimize_geometry(forcefield, steps)` with `MMFF94`, "
"`MMFF94s`, `UFF`, `GAFF`, `Ghemical`. The energy unit for a force field is "
"available via the free function `forcefield_energy_unit`."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:37
msgid ""
"**Configurable / constrained minimization** — `Minimizer` + "
"`optimize_geometry_with`, and the pull-based `minimize` trajectory iterator. "
"See [Key Concepts](./concepts.md#constrained-minimization)."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:41
msgid "Charges, atom chemistry & identifiers"
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:43
msgid ""
"**Partial charges** — `compute_charges(model)` with `gasteiger`, `mmff94`, "
"`eem`, `eqeq`, `qeq`, `qtpie`; per-atom values via `Atom::partial_charge`."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:45
msgid ""
"**Atom chemistry** — `degree`, `total_valence`, `implicit_hydrogens`, "
"`hybridization`, `is_hbond_donor`, `is_hbond_acceptor`."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:47
msgid ""
"**Identifiers** — `inchi` / `inchikey`, backed by the InChI library bundled "
"with OpenBabel."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:50
msgid "Geometry & structure alignment"
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:52
msgid ""
"**Alignment** — `align_to` / `align_to_with` least-squares-superpose one "
"molecule onto another (Kabsch), returning the RMSD and updating coordinates "
"in place. Backed by `OBAlign` (enabled by the vendored Eigen). See [Key "
"Concepts](./concepts.md#structure-alignment)."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:56
msgid "**Measurements** — `center`, `angle`, `torsion`."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:58
msgid "2D depiction"
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:60
msgid ""
"**SVG** — `to_svg` / `to_svg_with(SvgOptions)` render a molecule to an SVG "
"image; 2D coordinates are laid out automatically. Also `generate_2d` / "
"`has_2d`. The SVG painter is built in (no Cairo dependency)."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:64
msgid "Stereochemistry"
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:66
msgid ""
"Perceive and query stereocenters: `tetrahedral_stereo_count`, "
"`cistrans_stereo_count`, `perceive_stereo`; `Atom::is_tetrahedral_stereo` / "
"`stereo_winding` (a \\[`Winding`\\], clockwise/anticlockwise — OpenBabel's "
"descriptor, not a CIP `R`/`S` label); `Bond::is_cistrans_stereo`."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:71
msgid "Reaction / SMIRKS-like transforms"
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:73
msgid ""
"`Transform::new(reactant_smarts, product_smarts)` compiles a SMARTS→SMARTS "
"edit; `Transform::apply(&mut mol)` rewrites every match in place. See [Key "
"Concepts](./concepts.md#smarts-to-smarts-transforms)."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:77 src\concepts.md:133
msgid "Conformer search"
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:79
msgid ""
"`generate_conformers(count)` runs a genetic-algorithm conformer search "
"(needs a 3D structure); walk results with `num_conformers` / `set_conformer` "
"and score each with `energy`."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:83
msgid "Element data & extended queries"
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:85
msgid ""
"**`elements` module** — periodic-table data: `symbol`, `name`, "
"`atomic_number`, `mass`, `exact_mass`, `electronegativity`, "
"`covalent_radius`, `vdw_radius`, `max_bonds`."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:88
msgid ""
"**Richer atom queries** — `type_name`, `isotope`, `atomic_mass`, "
"`exact_mass`, `spin_multiplicity`, `heavy_degree`, `hetero_degree`, "
"`is_chiral`, `is_heteroatom`, `is_metal`, `is_polar_hydrogen`, and ring "
"queries (`ring_count`, `smallest_ring_size`, `is_in_ring_size`)."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:92
msgid ""
"**Richer bond queries** — `length`, `equilibrium_length`, `is_rotor`, "
"`is_amide`, `is_ester`, `is_carbonyl`, `is_closure`."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:94
msgid ""
"**Molecule extras** — `num_heavy_atoms`, `num_rings`, `num_rotatable_bonds`, "
"`spaced_formula`, `spin_multiplicity`, `clone`, `strip_salts`, `separate` "
"(into fragments), and string `property` / `set_property` metadata."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:98
msgid "Residues (biopolymer / PDB substructure)"
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:100
msgid ""
"`num_residues` / `residue` / `residues` expose the residue grouping that PDB "
"and mmCIF carry. A \\[`Residue`\\] reports `name`, `number` / "
"`number_string`, `chain`, `insertion_code`, atom counts, and its member "
"`atoms`. From the atom side, `Atom::residue` links back, with "
"`residue_atom_id`, `is_hetatm`, and `serial_number`. Molecules parsed from "
"SMILES carry no residues — the API never synthesizes one."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:107
msgid "Spectra"
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:109
msgid ""
"`spectrophore` computes the Spectrophore™ descriptor (48 values by default) "
"from a 3D structure — a rotation-invariant shape/property fingerprint."
msgstr ""

#: src\feature-tour.md:111
msgid ""
"`vibration_frequencies` / `vibration_intensities` read vibrational data when "
"the molecule was parsed from a computational-chemistry output that carries "
"it."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:3
msgid ""
"A closer look at the parts of the API whose behavior is subtle enough to be "
"worth explaining in prose. Each section links to the types involved; the "
"[API Reference](./api-reference.md) has the exact signatures."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:7
msgid "SMARTS-to-SMARTS transforms"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:9
msgid ""
"`Transform` compiles a **SMARTS→SMARTS edit** (OpenBabel's `OBChemTsfm`, the "
"engine behind SMIRKS-like reaction rules) and applies it to a molecule in "
"place."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:15
msgid "// Deprotonate a carboxylic acid: O–H on a C(=O)–O becomes O⁻.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:17
msgid "\"[C:1](=O)[OX2:2][H]\""
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:17
msgid "\"[C:1](=O)[O-:2]\""
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:18
msgid "\"valid transform\""
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:19
msgid "\"CC(=O)O\""
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:19
msgid "// acetic acid\n"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:20
msgid "// number of matches rewritten\n"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:26
msgid ""
"The key mechanism to understand is the **class labels** (`:1`, `:2`, …). "
"They tie an atom in the reactant pattern to the same atom in the product "
"pattern, so the transform knows _which_ atoms persist versus which are added "
"or removed. A transform can change formal charges and bond orders, and "
"delete atoms (for example, dropping the hydrogen when deprotonating). "
"`apply` returns how many matches it rewrote, and rewrites **all** of them."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:33
msgid ""
"This is the single densest concept in the crate — if a transform does "
"nothing, the usual cause is a reactant pattern that doesn't match, or class "
"labels that don't line up between the two sides."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:37
msgid "Constrained minimization"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:39
msgid "Force-field minimization is exposed in two layers."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:41
msgid ""
"The simple path is `Molecule::optimize_geometry(forcefield, steps)`, which "
"minimizes in one shot and returns the final energy."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:44
msgid ""
"For control, build a `Minimizer` — it bundles the force field, an "
"`Algorithm` (steepest descent / conjugate gradients / L-BFGS), a step "
"budget, an energy-convergence threshold, and an optional `Constraints` set:"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:55 src\concepts.md:107
msgid "\"MMFF94\""
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:60
msgid "// One-shot: returns the final energy.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:66
msgid "Two things to keep in mind:"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:68
msgid ""
"**Convergence is energy-only.** OpenBabel 3.2.1 lets you set the _energy_ "
"criterion (`energy_convergence`); it combines that with a _fixed_ internal "
"gradient criterion for which there is no public setter. So this API does not "
"expose a gradient tolerance — by design, not by omission."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:72
msgid ""
"**Builder methods take `&mut self` and return `&mut Self`,** so they chain "
"and can be applied conditionally."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:75
msgid "The `Constraints` builder"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:77
msgid ""
"A `Constraints` set restrains a minimization. All atom indices are "
"**0-based** (matching `Atom::index`). You can hold atoms fixed, pin a single "
"Cartesian axis, restrain distances/angles/torsions to target values, exclude "
"atoms entirely, and tune the restraint stiffness:"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:86
msgid "// hold atom 0 in place\n"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:87
msgid "// pin the 1–2 bond to 1.54 Å\n"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:88
msgid "// stiffen the restraints\n"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:91
msgid "Pass the set to a `Minimizer` with `Minimizer::constraints`."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:93
msgid "The pull-based optimization trajectory"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:95
msgid ""
"`Molecule::minimize(&cfg)` does **not** minimize immediately. It returns an "
"`Optimization` — a lazy `Iterator` that advances the minimization by "
"`steps_per_frame` steps on each `next()` and yields an `OptStep` (cumulative "
"step count, energy, and coordinates) per frame. Iteration ends at "
"convergence or the step budget, leaving the molecule holding the final "
"geometry."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:110
msgid "\"step {:>4}  E = {:.4}\""
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:111
msgid "// log it, collect it, or `break` to stop early.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:116
msgid ""
"Because the trajectory drives the parent molecule's coordinates, the "
"iterator **borrows the molecule mutably**. That means: read each frame's "
"geometry from the yielded `OptStep`, not from the molecule, while iterating "
"— the molecule is borrowed for the duration of the loop."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:121
msgid "Structure alignment"
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:123
msgid ""
"`Molecule::align_to(&reference)` least-squares-superposes the molecule onto "
"a reference (the Kabsch algorithm, via OpenBabel's `OBAlign`), returns the "
"RMSD, and updates the aligned molecule's coordinates in place. "
"`align_to_with` exposes options (such as whether to include hydrogens and "
"whether to use symmetry)."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:128
msgid ""
"The important precondition: the default alignment assumes the **two "
"molecules have the same atom order**. It is ideal for comparing conformers "
"or poses of the same molecule (identical structures align to ~0 RMSD), not "
"for matching two arbitrarily-ordered molecules."
msgstr ""

#: src\concepts.md:135
msgid ""
"`Molecule::generate_conformers(count)` runs a genetic-algorithm conformer "
"search and returns how many conformers it produced. It **requires an "
"existing 3D structure** (call `generate_3d` first). Walk the results with "
"`num_conformers` and `set_conformer`, and score each with `energy`. Like "
"alignment and distance-geometry generation, it relies on the vendored Eigen "
"support."
msgstr ""

#: src\building.md:3
msgid "Requirements"
msgstr ""

#: src\building.md:5
msgid "**Rust** (MSVC toolchain on Windows)."
msgstr ""

#: src\building.md:7
msgid "**Submodules checked out**: `git submodule update --init --recursive`."
msgstr ""

#: src\building.md:12
msgid "\"c1ccccc1\"   # benzene\n"
msgstr ""

#: src\building.md:15
msgid ""
"The **first** build compiles all of OpenBabel from source and takes ~10–20 "
"minutes. Subsequent builds are incremental and fast."
msgstr ""

#: src\building.md:18
msgid "Why building can be slow the first time"
msgstr ""

#: src\building.md:20
msgid ""
"`openbabel-sys/build.rs` compiles OpenBabel from the `vendor/openbabel-src` "
"submodule (via CMake) and links it, rather than relying on a system install. "
"This keeps the binding self-contained and version-matched, at the cost of a "
"long initial build. CMake caches its work, so later `cargo build`s are "
"no-ops for the C++ side unless the shim or the cxx bridge changes. See "
"[Architecture → Building OpenBabel from "
"source](./architecture.md#building-openbabel-from-source)."
msgstr ""

#: src\building.md:27
msgid "Windows / MSVC specifics"
msgstr ""

#: src\building.md:29
msgid "`build.rs` handles three Windows/MSVC details that are easy to trip over:"
msgstr ""

#: src\building.md:31
msgid ""
"**C++ flags.** The `cmake` crate replaces `CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS`, dropping the "
"`/DWIN32 /D_WINDOWS /EHsc /GR` that OpenBabel relies on (for example, its "
"`strcasecmp` shim is guarded by `#if defined(WIN32)`); `build.rs` adds them "
"back."
msgstr ""

#: src\building.md:35
msgid ""
"**Plugin & DLL discovery.** OpenBabel discovers its format plugins (`.obf`) "
"in the directory of `openbabel-3.dll` (not via `BABEL_LIBDIR` on Windows), "
"so `build.rs` copies the DLL **and** the plugins next to the test/exe "
"binaries. Data files are located via `BABEL_DATADIR`, which the safe wrapper "
"sets through the C runtime so OpenBabel's `getenv` observes it (see "
"[Architecture → Runtime "
"initialization](./architecture.md#runtime-initialization-finding-plugins-and-data))."
msgstr ""

#: src\building.md:41
msgid ""
"**Bundled InChI on MSVC.** Building the bundled InChI from source needs two "
"fixes, both applied by `build.rs`: OpenBabel force-sets "
"`OPENBABEL_USE_SYSTEM_INCHI=ON` when `OB_USE_PREBUILT_BINARIES` is on (its "
"MSVC default), which would demand a system InChI we don't have — so "
"`build.rs` turns that off; and the vendored InChI omits four AuxInfo "
"functions its ABI wrappers reference, so `build.rs` drops inert stubs into "
"the InChI tree so `inchi.dll` links. Both are runtime-inert (OpenBabel never "
"calls those functions for InChI output). `inchi.dll` is copied alongside the "
"other runtime DLLs."
msgstr ""

#: src\building.md:51
msgid "Runtime data files"
msgstr ""

#: src\building.md:53
msgid ""
"At runtime, OpenBabel needs its plugin (`.obf`) and data directories. "
"`build.rs` bakes their paths into a generated `paths.rs`, and the safe API's "
"`init()` points `BABEL_LIBDIR` / `BABEL_DATADIR` at the bundled copies "
"through the C runtime. You do not need to set any environment variables "
"yourself."
msgstr ""

